    "question": "What altitude(s) are appropriate and why?",
    "correctAnswer": "Per 91.159, when flying VFR above 3,000 AGL: for magnetic course 0–179°, use odd thousands + 500 (e.g., 3,500; 5,500; 7,500). For 180–359°, use even thousands + 500. Since my course is 090°, I plan an odd + 500 altitude that also respects terrain and airspace (e.g., 5,500 or 7,500 depending on MEFs and clouds).",
    "trapReasoning": "“VFR altitudes are optional. Any altitude is fine as long as you’re not in controlled airspace.”",
    "whyThisMatters": "This is a simple rule that prevents head-on conflicts and shows planning professionalism. The DPE is checking whether you apply regulations to a real flight plan, not just recite them.",
    "cramMode": "Above 3,000 AGL: 0–179° = odd + 500; 180–359° = even + 500. Then verify terrain/airspace/weather.",
