    "question": "What does 91.211 require, and what’s the smart operational choice?",
    "correctAnswer": "Legally, 91.211 requires oxygen for crew above 12,500 MSL for more than 30 minutes, and continuously above 14,000; passengers must have oxygen available above 15,000. At 11,500, it’s not legally required, but it can still be smart to use oxygen depending on symptoms, time, and individual susceptibility — especially at night. If anyone feels impaired, I descend and/or use supplemental oxygen if available.",
    "trapReasoning": "“If oxygen isn’t legally required, it can’t help. Feeling off is just anxiety.”",
    "whyThisMatters": "Hypoxia is subtle and varies by person. The DPE wants to see you separate legal minimums from safe physiology and make conservative choices when symptoms appear.",
    "cramMode": "Legal oxygen starts at 12,500 (>30 min), but smart oxygen can start lower. If symptoms show up, descend — don’t debate it.",
    "reference": "14 CFR 91.211",
