    "airports": "KSDL (Scottsdale)",
    "aircraft": "Cessna 172",
    "scenario": "You’re turning from base to final and notice you’re going to overshoot. You add inside rudder to “tighten it up” while holding bank angle. The airplane starts to feel mushy.",
    "question": "Is this a skid or a slip, and why is it dangerous?",
    "correctAnswer": "Inside rudder in a turn tends to create a **skid** (too much yaw into the turn). In a skid, the airplane’s tendency at the stall is to roll and yaw aggressively — a classic spin entry. Close to the ground, there’s no time to recover. The correct response is reduce angle of attack (lower the nose), level wings as needed, and go around.",
    "trapReasoning": "“More rudder always helps you turn tighter safely.”",
    "whyThisMatters": "The DPE is testing whether you understand the aerodynamic reason behind the base-to-final stall/spin accident pattern: skidding turns at low altitude.",
