    "topic": "Stalls - Cross-Control Inputs and Wing Drop",
    "airports": "KPAO (Palo Alto) practice area",
    "aircraft": "DA40",
    "scenario": "In slow flight, you’re holding excessive rudder in one direction and opposite aileron to “keep it straight.” The stall horn chirps and the airplane rolls unexpectedly.",
    "question": "What’s happening aerodynamically, and what’s your recovery?",
    "correctAnswer": "Cross-control creates unequal lift/drag on the wings and can put one wing at a higher angle of attack than the other. Near the stall, that wing stalls first and drops. Recovery: reduce AoA (lower the nose), level wings with coordinated controls, add power as appropriate, and re-establish coordinated flight. Don’t fight the roll with more aileron at the stall.",
    "trapReasoning": "“If a wing drops, add opposite aileron while holding rudder — that will stop it.”",
